Note: The answers reflect what issues tenants could first think of when
asked. Not mentioning the issue does not mean that they are not having the
issue.

COVID-19 Rent and Mutual Aid

   -

   We have received 7 responses to our COVID-19 Rent & Mutual Aid Survey
   <https://forms.gle/yWZo2gvGK26EAr2L8>. If you are experiencing rent
   affordability issues, need support from neighbors (such as groceries or
   laundry), or want to volunteer to help neighbors, please fill out the
   survey <https://forms.gle/yWZo2gvGK26EAr2L8>.
   -

   A few people have told us that COVID-19 has affected their ability to
   afford rent. We don=E2=80=99t know yet what action can be taken that wou=
ld be
   effective. We will have a follow-up meeting separately. Please email us =
if
   you=E2=80=99re interested.
   -

   We are making some fabric masks to give away, which we will try to give
   out next week. Let us know if you need child sizes.


Questions we asked meeting attendees:

   -

   Do you have any useful contacts (for example, people who are
   knowledgeable about tenants rights or housing codes)?
   -

   Do you know of any apartment units that are unoccupied (because they
   moved out)?
   -

   Are you interested in becoming a point person for your building?
   (Building liaison)
   -

   Do you have any skills that might be useful for the tenants association?
   -

   What issues or goals do you want our association to address?
   -

   Are you Spanish-English bilingual and willing to be a liaison or
   organizer for tenants who mostly speak Spanish?
   -

   Are you friends with other neighbors? Ask them if they have joined the
   tenants association. If not, please have them contact us:
   hayescourtunited@gmail.com or text/call 510-671-1372.


NEXT MEETING: Tuesday, May 5, 2020, 7 PM. Join by video chat or by phone.

Details on how to join the call will be emailed out before the meeting.



__________________________________________




Other meeting notes..:

   -

   Regarding the written complaint to management as a collective: It is
   unlikely that they will respond, BUT, that written complaint should incl=
ude
   all existing maintenance issues, repairs, etc. and also addresses the fa=
ct
   that we need an on-site super. We are doing this because we want a paper
   trail of proof that management knows about these issues. If we want to d=
o
   something in the future (such as withhold rent), we will now have a pape=
r
   trail. PS, that process of withholding rent is risky and requires furthe=
r
   research. What we would ideally need to do is pay our rent into an escro=
w
   account.
   -

   We don=E2=80=99t want to use this association to solve neighbor disputes=
, but we
   are willing to help facilitate a conversation between neighbors.
   -

   Regarding the complaint form: Is there any risk of retaliation? Would it
   be as effective if anonymous? We need to research this.
   -

   L: Shouldn=E2=80=99t 311 be done after contacting management? Us: We don=
=E2=80=99t think
   so, because 311 can be done anonymously and creates an important record
   that the city owns.
   -

   Rent stabilization status is something we want to tackle farther down
   the road.
   -

   We will organize email groups for people who agreed to share info with
   their building line.
   -

   We may also get some advice through 311 housing experts.
   -

   N: volunteers to be liaison for building G.
   -

   N: wants to help with outreach to previous tenants association.
   -

   N: We did send documents to management. When we took action 2 years ago,
   we didn=E2=80=99t reveal who was part of the tenants association.
   -

   N: Chhaya in Jackson Heights may be a useful contact, contact Rima;
   Queens Legal Services was involved early on but lost interest because th=
eir
   income requirements are too high, but maybe we can try again because of
   COVID-19 crisis.
   -

   Is management tampering with rent histories? --  N: For our unit, maybe.
   We have some rent histories from the past that we can use for comparison=
 to
   new rent histories requested. I still need to ask permission from previo=
us
   tenants. Us: We have a potential contact who can tell us whether managem=
ent
   is tampering with rent histories or rent stabilization.
   -

   We can share our timeline (future tasks) in a separate email.
   -

   We are very concerned about heat and hot water, and we have fact sheets
   about calling 311 that we will deliver.


Best,
Your neighbors / Hayes Court United

